<div id="review_643990455" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/643990455" />
    <a title="Denise Cornelius" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9367611-denise-cornelius"><img alt="Denise Cornelius" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468514453p2/9367611.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/643990455?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Denise Cornelius" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Denise Cornelius" href="/user/show/9367611-denise-cornelius">Denise Cornelius</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer643990455&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer643990455" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4792169040713576041">This book has a great setup and a horrible ending. <br/><br/><br/>Kate&apos;s daughter Amelia supposedly commits suicide, but alas someone sends Kate a text insinuating it was murder. The book goes back in forth between Amelia&apos;s life before she died, Kate in present, and Kate in the past (when she realized she was pregnant with Amelia). One of the chief problems with this book is character development. Really, there isn&apos;t any and you don&apos;t get to know any of the characters well enough to really care except for Amel</span>
  <span id="freeText4792169040713576041" style="display:none">This book has a great setup and a horrible ending. <br /><br /><br />Kate's daughter Amelia supposedly commits suicide, but alas someone sends Kate a text insinuating it was murder. The book goes back in forth between Amelia's life before she died, Kate in present, and Kate in the past (when she realized she was pregnant with Amelia). One of the chief problems with this book is character development. Really, there isn't any and you don't get to know any of the characters well enough to really care except for Amelia. The plot really keeps the book going and then at the end...it kind of doesn't amount to much. It really could have been a much better book than it was. <br /><br /><br />Also, all the flashbacks for Kate are awful because they really don't give you a sense of who she is or her motivations. I mean everything you learn in the flashbacks you could really surmise for the most part. <br /><br />Stop, spoiler time:<br /><br />Amelia: Amelia is killed by her friend Sylvia when she thinks that Amelia fooled around with her boyfriend. However it was a setup by this secret society Amelia joined that turned on her. Sylvia even before the murder/accident (it never really specifies which) is an awful friend. Also, she is one who sends the text that Amelia was not murdered, yet doesn't come forward and isn't forthcoming with any information until the end when forced<br /><br />Secret Society- Amelia joins one, She falls for one of the girls. They turn on her and make her life miserable. <br /><br />Amelia mysterious texter fried Ben is really William her father (that she doesn't know about) pretending to be a 16 year old kid to get to know her...yeah what??? I pretty much knew by the second chapter that Ben was fake. <br /><br />Kate: Amelia's father is William even though Kate spends most of the book thinking it's Daniel. It's kind of a big, who cares...since you barely know either one. There a million opportunities to develop either William or Daniel's character and it never happens. <br /><br />Kate ends up at the end with one of Amelia's teachers who you also never get to know...so who cares...<br /><br />The worst part of the book is that you are on the edge of your seat to know things and then you find out... and it's a let down. Also, that you get just enough info to be curious about the characters and then nothing...<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4792169040713576041" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


